The issue was that `UserInputEmailAddressParser` accepted email addresses with a trailing slash, such as `xxx@gmail.com/`, because the underlying `mime4j` parser is permissive. These addresses are not valid RFC-5321 addresses and sending them results in failure.

I fixed this by modifying `legacy/ui/legacy/src/main/java/com/fsck/k9/view/UserInputEmailAddressParser.kt` to explicitly reject addresses where the hostname contains a `/`.

The fix involved:
1.  Adding a `hasInvalidHostname()` extension function to `Address` within `UserInputEmailAddressParser`.
2.  Updating the `parse()` function to filter out addresses where `hasInvalidHostname()` returns true.

I verified the fix with a reproduction test case and ensured that existing tests still pass.

```kotlin
    fun parse(input: String): List<Address> {
        return Address.parseUnencoded(input)
            .mapNotNull { address ->
                when {
                    address.isIncomplete() -> null
                    address.hasInvalidHostname() -> null
                    address.isNonAsciiAddress() -> throw NonAsciiEmailAddressException(address.address)
                    else -> Address.parse(address.toEncodedString()).firstOrNull()
                }
            }
    }

    private fun Address.isIncomplete() = hostname.isNullOrBlank()

    private fun Address.hasInvalidHostname() = hostname?.contains("/") == true
